# Kubernetes Admission Control – OPA Gatekeeper & Kyverno Documentation

---

## 1. Introduction

Admission Controllers in Kubernetes validate and control requests before they are persisted in the cluster.

Flow:
User → kubectl apply → API Server → Admission Controller → Allow/Deny → etcd

Policy engines:

* OPA Gatekeeper (uses Rego)
* Kyverno (uses YAML)

---

## 2. OPA Gatekeeper

### 2.1 Key Concepts

* ConstraintTemplate → Defines policy logic
* Constraint → Applies the policy
* Rego → Policy language

---

### 2.2 Installation

kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/open-policy-agent/gatekeeper/master/deploy/gatekeeper.yaml

---

### 2.3 Example Policy – Block Latest Image

ConstraintTemplate:

apiVersion: templates.gatekeeper.sh/v1beta1
kind: ConstraintTemplate
metadata:
name: k8snotlatest
spec:
crd:
spec:
names:
kind: K8sNotLatest
targets:
- target: admission.k8s.gatekeeper.sh
rego: |
package k8snotlatest

```
    violation[{"msg": msg}] {
      container := input.review.object.spec.containers[_]
      endswith(container.image, ":latest")
      msg := "Latest image not allowed"
    }
```

---

Constraint:

apiVersion: constraints.gatekeeper.sh/v1beta1
kind: K8sNotLatest
metadata:
name: no-latest
spec:
match:
kinds:
- apiGroups: [""]
kinds: ["Pod"]

---

### 2.4 Important Notes

* Both Template and Constraint are required
* Policies apply to all resources
* Always exclude system namespaces:

spec:
match:
excludedNamespaces:
- kube-system
- gatekeeper-system
- kyverno

---

### 2.5 Common OPA Policies

* No latest image
* Required labels
* Resource limits required
* No privileged containers
* Allowed registries

---

## 3. Kyverno

### 3.1 Key Concepts

* ClusterPolicy → Single YAML for policy
* Rule → Defines validation logic
* Pattern → YAML-based matching

---

### 3.2 Installation

kubectl create -f https://github.com/kyverno/kyverno/releases/latest/download/install.yaml

---

### 3.3 Example Policy – Block Latest Image

apiVersion: kyverno.io/v1
kind: ClusterPolicy
metadata:
name: no-latest-tag

spec:
validationFailureAction: Enforce
rules:
- name: block-latest
match:
resources:
kinds:
- Pod
validate:
message: "Latest image not allowed"
pattern:
spec:
containers:
- image: "!*:latest"

---

### 3.4 Kyverno Modes

* Enforce → Blocks resource
* Audit → Allows but logs warning
* Mutate → Modifies resource automatically

---

### 3.5 Example – Required Labels

validate:
message: "Label app is required"
pattern:
metadata:
labels:
app: "?*"

---

## 4. OPA vs Kyverno

## Feature                OPA Gatekeeper        Kyverno

Language              Rego                  YAML
Files Required        2                     1
Ease of Use           Medium                Easy
Flexibility           High                  Medium
Kubernetes Native     No                    Yes

---

## 5. Troubleshooting (Real Scenario)

Issue:
Kyverno pods not created

Root Cause:
OPA policy (resource limits) blocked Kyverno pods

Error:
denied by admission webhook "validation.gatekeeper.sh"
CPU limit required

Fix:

kubectl delete k8sresourcelimits resource-limits

kubectl rollout restart deploy -n kyverno

---

## 6. Debug Commands

kubectl get events -n <namespace>
kubectl describe deploy <name>
kubectl get constraints
kubectl get pods -n <namespace>

---

## 7. Summary

* OPA Gatekeeper uses Rego and requires two YAML files
* Kyverno uses native YAML and is simpler
* Admission controllers affect all resources including system components
* Always exclude system namespaces to avoid blocking core services

